Rating: 1
I have gotten far better results simply roasting a salted, peppered, and oiled chicken at 400 degrees until the internal temperature hits 170 degrees. There are problems with this recipe. The low oven temperature and frequent basting mean that the bird is in the oven for a long time and that it dries out. Spraying the bird with orange juice dries it out even more. A better method is to roast the bird with the fruit inside and then to drizzle the warm fruit juice after the bird has cooked. The sauce includes ingredients not always kept on hand and extra pans to clean are generated in making the sauce. In the end, the bird was neither flavorful nor moist. Given a choice of investing the time and money in this preparation or simply buying a store bought rotisserie bird, I'd go for the store bought bird and spend my time and money in some other fashion. I wonder what the editorial staff is doing? Untested internet recipes are a no less risky venture than this mess.

